In order to help us better understand your request for a barrier; please visit the link below to download a request form to provide some background information on your request. Upon receipt of the completed form  engineering staff will review the form and any supporting documentation and perform a site visit for a safety evaluation. Based on the information provided and the site evaluation  we will determine what safety measures (if any) can be implemented in response to your request.     Please note that the completion of this form does not guarantee a barrier will be installed. Other safety measures such as signage  lighting  and/or changes to roadway geometry may also be implemented to address safety concerns instead of  or in addition to  your request for a barrier.    If you have any questions  please contact the Public Works Department Engineering Division at 617-635-4968 or at pwdengineering@boston.gov.  Again  we appreciate and thank you for your interest in public safety and the welfare of your community.    Barrier Request Form:    https://attachments.cityofboston.gov/?f=23434&fid=e2371fad

Closed date : 2018-02-01 08:06:25.44 Case Resolved   Dear Constituent     The Boston Public Works Construction Inspection Unit (CIU) Inspector has identified that vault on the sidewalk needing attention as the responsibility of Eversource Electric.     Replacing or repairing vaults is not an easy repair.      Eversource has to have the vaults custom made for each separate location.      This takes time.  In addition the construction itself is technical and involved  as well as expensive.     We have informed Eversource Electric that they have to set aside resources to repair vaults around the City.    The estimated time for replacement is 6-9 months.      However  we will require Eversource to make a temporary repair such as the use of asphalt  especially if it is a major tripping hazard.     The temporary repair should be done within 3 business days.     For any questions or concern  please contact the number listed below    Sincerely     Mark Cardarelli  Supervisor of Utility Coordination and Compliance  Boston Public Works Department  617-635-4951 Office
SUBJECT: Public Works Department

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed. Closed date : 2018-02-06 17:45:54.013 Case Noted The restriping of Beacon Street was implemented as part of the City's Vision Zero program with the principle goals of reducing motorist speeds  providing greater safety in pedestrian crossings  and delineating a better protected space for cyclists to use the corridor.  Because there is more roadway width on Beacon Street than is needed to process the volumes of vehicles present  the extra space was converted into a bicycle lane and additional buffers for pedestrians.   We do understand that the changes to the roadway are not commonly experienced in the City just yet  and we are asking all users (cyclists included) to be considerate and conscientious while making use of the street. Flyers have been distributed to buildings along Beacon Street and two information signs were hung up along each block in order to assist motorists and cyclists in knowing where they should be and how they should be using the various spaces in the street.  I would certainly say that it was not appropriate for that individual to have yelled at you. Perhaps a clarifying conversation with you might have been more constructive  especially between two persons representing different transportation modes. Less yelling  more speaking  is my thought.  The pavement markings installed as part of this change provide a parking lane of 8.5 feet  an additional passenger side buffer of 3 feet  and a bike lane of 6 feet. The additional space allocated to the parking lane  which are normally 7-7.5 feet  was intended to provide a bit more room for motorists to park appropriately and comfortably in the lane.  The buffer of 3 feet is intended to provide persons with a standing space between the vehicle parking lane and the bicycle lane.  This space is designed to be where doors may be opened  groceries and packages taken out  and/or a place to safely stand to wait before crossing the bicycle lane.  The loading/drop-off zone signed in front of #330 Beacon Street was retained by request of the nearby residents. This does continue to designate the two-vehicle space between the signs for this use. However  this designation affects the area within the parking lane away from the curb. The loading zone and the bicycle lane do not merge  but are positioned in parallel to one another.   As they would on the driver?s side of the vehicle with the travel lane  it is the responsibility of the driver/passenger(s) to be conscientious about any cyclists approaching in the bike lane.  However  it is absolutely a courteous and collaborative progress toward cultivating safe and low-speed use of our City fabric for cyclists to make efforts to yield if a pedestrian were trying to cross the lane to the sidewalk.  The bicycle lane is to be treated as a standard vehicle lane on the roadway.  In our dense urban environment  cyclists yielding to persons making deliveries or drop-offs at this space is a considerate and safe maneuver  but not a requirement. The buffer installed between the parking areas and the bike lane is intended to provide space for standing while the interaction is navigated carefully.  It should also be emphasized that we regularly recommend that cyclists monitor and moderate their speeds of travel  especially when the context area is designed more for people than vehicles. While much less dangerous than speeding behaviors by motorists  a cyclist moving along at a significant speed does create an environment of anxiety for and risk of collision with pedestrians. This relationship is not conducive to the partnership that cyclists and pedestrians should have together  as they are both relatively vulnerable roadway users when compared with motor vehicles.
SUBJECT: Mayor's 24 Hour Hotline
TYPE: General Comments For a Program or Policy
